ile\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_main_2527449\" data-toggle=\"modal\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Okt 06, 2024</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent wide\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104fct1665702908434.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/fct1665702908434.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/fct1665702908434.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"fct1665702908434\" role=\"article\">\n<h1 class=\"title topictitle1\" id=\"ariaid-title1\">\n                 \n Web Application Vulnerablities\n   </h1>\n<div class=\"body conbody\" id=\"fct1665702908434__web_application_vulnerablities_127922\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">Almost every area of a web application, from configuration to data I/O, and from auuthentication to logging needs to be considered when looking at web security.\n </p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"fct1665702908434__p_d40907e1_d40908e1_d40909e1\">In general you need to be consider the following issues when developing your web application:</p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20492e1_d20493e1_d20494e1\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"fct1665702908434__p_d40910e1_d40911e1_d40912e1\">Identity spoofing—you need to prevent users from\n               acting as if they were any other user, or assuming another user's identity. For more\n               details, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"rrs1665702669390.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/rrs1665702669390.html\" title=\"Authentication is intended to ensure that users (or computers) accessing the system or application are who they purport to be. Authentication systems range in strength from simple user and password validation to transaction signing.\">Authentication for Web Applications</a> and <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"pii1665702668200.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/pii1665702668200.html\" title=\"Session management is intended to provide a robust and cryptographically secure association between authenticated users and their sessions. Using session management combined with secure HTTP (HTTPS), you can enforce authorization checks and prevent common attacks such as replay attacks, request forging, and man-in-the-middle attacks.\">Session Management for Web Applications</a>.</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20495e1_d20496e1_d20497e1\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"fct1665702908434__p_d40913e1_d40914e1_d40915e1\">Data tampering—users can change any data delivered to them and this can change client-side validation, GET data, POST data, cookies, HTTP headers, and so on. The application should not send data to the browser that is obtainable from within the browser itself. In addition, the application should carefully check any data received from the user to identify if it is sane and applicable. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"tiy1665702897331.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/tiy1665702897331.html\" title=\"In web applications, it is possible for the client to tamper with data, so data from the client should never be trusted. Failure to properly validate input from the client or the environment is a security weakness.\">Data I/O for Web Applications</a>.</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20498e1_d20499e1_d20500e1\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"fct1665702908434__p_d40916e1_d40917e1_d40918e1\">Elevation of privilege—if an application provides\n               users and administrative roles, it is vital to ensure the users cannot elevate\n               themselves to any higher privilege role, by ensuring all actions must be gated\n               through an authorization matrix to ensure that only the right roles can access\n               privileged functionality. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"evz1665702908556.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/evz1665702908556.html\" title=\"Authorization ensures that users have appropriate privileges to perform actions or access resources.\">Authorization for Web Applications</a>. </p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20501e1_d20502e1_d20503e1\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"fct1665702908434__p_d40919e1_d40920e1_d40921e1\">Information disclosure—the browser cannot be trusted fully to adhere to no-caching policies that can be set by HTTP headers. It is therefore important to minimize the amount of information stored by a browser, just in case it leaks information that could be used by an attacker to learn more about the user or even become that user. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"oxa1665702908679.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/oxa1665702908679.html\" title=\"Web browsers are the clients in a web application, responsible for sending and receiving data to and from the server. The browser interprets and displays HTML, and makes use of interpreters for programming scripts such as JavaScript, PHP, and Flash. It is therefore vulnerable to attacks that intercept and read the data it sends, or cross-site scripting attacks such as site forgery.\">Browser Security</a>.</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20504e1_d20505e1_d20506e1\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"fct1665702908434__p_d40922e1_d40923e1_d40924e1\">Denial of service—applications could be abused by a\n               denial-of-service attack, in which requests claim expensive resources, thereby\n               impairing service to other users. Such requests should be reserved for authorized\n               users. See <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"rrs1665702669390.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/rrs1665702669390.html\" title=\"Authentication is intended to ensure that users (or computers) accessing the system or application are who they purport to be. Authentication systems range in strength from simple user and password validation to transaction signing.\">Authentication for Web Applications</a> and <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"evz1665702908556.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/evz1665702908556.html\" title=\"Authorization ensures that users have appropriate privileges to perform actions or access resources.\">Authorization for Web Applications</a>. </p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20507e1_d20508e1_d20509e1\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"fct1665702908434__p_d40925e1_d40926e1_d40927e1\">Repudiation—applications should have repudiation\n               controls, such as web access logs and audit trails at every tier as well as a user\n               context from top to bottom. Ideally the application should run as the user, but\n               within Uniface this is not possible. See <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"xwm1665702708046.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/xwm1665702708046.html\" title=\"Auditing access and activity logs on a regular basis helps in detecting attempted or successful intrusions. If there has been unauthorized access of your web application, you need to be able to show the signs of intrusion and prove a user's actions. You should also minimize the information provided in error pages.\">Logging and Auditing Web Applications</a>. </p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"fct1665702908434__p_d40928e1_d40929e1_d40930e1\">The following table shows the application areas that need to be considered in a web application, and the types of threats they are vulnerable to. The discussions of the security threats include information on how you can defend against them.</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table class=\"table\" count-columns=\"2\" id=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1\"><caption><span class=\"table--title-label\">Table 1. </span><span class=\"title\">Vulnerable Application Areas and Their Threats</span></caption><colgroup><col/><col/></colgroup><thead class=\"thead\">\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<th class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" id=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__1\">\n<p class=\"p\">Vulnerable Application Area</p>\n</th>\n<th class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" id=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__2\">\n<p class=\"p\">Threats</p>\n</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody class=\"tbody\">\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"rrs1665702669390.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/rrs1665702669390.html\" title=\"Authentication is intended to ensure that users (or computers) accessing the system or application are who they purport to be. Authentication systems range in strength from simple user and password validation to transaction signing.\">Authentication for Web Applications</a>\n</p>\n</td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__2\">\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20510e1_d20511e1_d20512e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"tcb1665702668270.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/tcb1665702668270.html\" title=\"Session fixation is a web security threat in which a user’s session ID is set to one known to an attacker.\">Session Fixation</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20513e1_d20514e1_d20515e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"olq1665702669163.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/olq1665702669163.html\" title=\"Session sidejacking is a type of security threat in which an attacker hijacks a session by intercepting and reading network traffic between two parties to steal the session cookie.\">Session Sidejacking</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20516e1_d20517e1_d20518e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"sht1665702669233.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/sht1665702669233.html\" title=\"Cross-site scripting vulnerabilities enable an attacker to trick the user’s browser into running code (such as JavaScript, Java, Flash, ActiveX, or VBScript) that is treated as trustworthy, thereby allowing the attacker to obtain a copy of the session ID or inject malicious code into web pages viewed by other users.\">Cross-Site Scripting</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20519e1_d20520e1_d20521e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"sit1665702545185.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/sit1665702545185.html\" title=\"In a man-in-the-middle (MITM) attack, an attacker intercepts a communication between two machines, and impersonates these machines. Both machines assume they are connected to the other, but they are actually connected to an attacker’s machine, which intercepts all messages, and then steals, monitors, or alters the information in it before sending it on to the machine that it was intended for, if it does so at all.\">Man-In-The-Middle Attacks</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20522e1_d20523e1_d20524e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"mzh1665702669302.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/mzh1665702669302.html\" title=\"Identity spoofing, or IP address spoofing, occurs when an attacker determines the IP address of a network, computer, or network component, and uses it to gain access or submit data under that identity, without being authorized to do so.\">Identity Spoofing</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20525e1_d20526e1_d20527e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"kcf1665702669602.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/kcf1665702669602.html\" title=\"When trying to crack user passwords, attackers can resort to guessing, dictionary attacks, and brute force attacks.\">Password Cracking</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"evz1665702908556.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/evz1665702908556.html\" title=\"Authorization ensures that users have appropriate privileges to perform actions or access resources.\">Authorization for Web Applications</a>\n</p>\n</td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__2\">\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20528e1_d20529e1_d20530e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">Access to confidential data</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20531e1_d20532e1_d20533e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">Data manipulation</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20534e1_d20535e1_d20536e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">Execution of unauthorized commands</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20537e1_d20538e1_d20539e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">Privilege escalation</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"oxa1665702908679.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/oxa1665702908679.html\" title=\"Web browsers are the clients in a web application, responsible for sending and receiving data to and from the server. The browser interprets and displays HTML, and makes use of interpreters for programming scripts such as JavaScript, PHP, and Flash. It is therefore vulnerable to attacks that intercept and read the data it sends, or cross-site scripting attacks such as site forgery.\">Browser Security</a>\n</p>\n</td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__2\">\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20540e1_d20541e1_d20542e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"ajn1665702669971.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/ajn1665702669971.html\" title=\"Eavesdropping is a web security threat in which intermediate servers or sniffer programs intercept and read HTTP data packets as they traverse intermediate servers en route to their destination.\">Eavesdropping</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20543e1_d20544e1_d20545e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"pxc1665702669673.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/pxc1665702669673.html\" title=\"Data leaks can result from incorrectly specified cookies, unverified client input, and verbose error messages.\">Data Leaks</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20546e1_d20547e1_d20548e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"sht1665702669233.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/sht1665702669233.html\" title=\"Cross-site scripting vulnerabilities enable an attacker to trick the user’s browser into running code (such as JavaScript, Java, Flash, ActiveX, or VBScript) that is treated as trustworthy, thereby allowing the attacker to obtain a copy of the session ID or inject malicious code into web pages viewed by other users.\">Cross-Site Scripting</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"pii1665702668200.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/pii1665702668200.html\" title=\"Session management is intended to provide a robust and cryptographically secure association between authenticated users and their sessions. Using session management combined with secure HTTP (HTTPS), you can enforce authorization checks and prevent common attacks such as replay attacks, request forging, and man-in-the-middle attacks.\">Session Management for Web Applications</a>\n</p>\n</td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__2\">\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20549e1_d20550e1_d20551e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"tcb1665702668270.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/tcb1665702668270.html\" title=\"Session fixation is a web security threat in which a user’s session ID is set to one known to an attacker.\">Session Fixation</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20552e1_d20553e1_d20554e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"olq1665702669163.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/olq1665702669163.html\" title=\"Session sidejacking is a type of security threat in which an attacker hijacks a session by intercepting and reading network traffic between two parties to steal the session cookie.\">Session Sidejacking</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20555e1_d20556e1_d20557e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"sht1665702669233.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/sht1665702669233.html\" title=\"Cross-site scripting vulnerabilities enable an attacker to trick the user’s browser into running code (such as JavaScript, Java, Flash, ActiveX, or VBScript) that is treated as trustworthy, thereby allowing the attacker to obtain a copy of the session ID or inject malicious code into web pages viewed by other users.\">Cross-Site Scripting</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"tiy1665702897331.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/tiy1665702897331.html\" title=\"In web applications, it is possible for the client to tamper with data, so data from the client should never be trusted. Failure to properly validate input from the client or the environment is a security weakness.\">Data I/O for Web Applications</a>\n</p>\n</td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__2\">\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20558e1_d20559e1_d20560e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"rnq1665702669823.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/rnq1665702669823.html\" title=\"Interpreter injection attacks send malicious code that is intended for execution by one of the interpreters that web applications use, both on the server side and in the browser. Common injection attacks include SQL injection, JavaScript injection, HTTP response splitting, and parameter manipulation.\">Interpreter Injection</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20561e1_d20562e1_d20563e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"sht1665702669233.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/sht1665702669233.html\" title=\"Cross-site scripting vulnerabilities enable an attacker to trick the user’s browser into running code (such as JavaScript, Java, Flash, ActiveX, or VBScript) that is treated as trustworthy, thereby allowing the attacker to obtain a copy of the session ID or inject malicious code into web pages viewed by other users.\">Cross-Site Scripting</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20564e1_d20565e1_d20566e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"sit1665702545185.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/sit1665702545185.html\" title=\"In a man-in-the-middle (MITM) attack, an attacker intercepts a communication between two machines, and impersonates these machines. Both machines assume they are connected to the other, but they are actually connected to an attacker’s machine, which intercepts all messages, and then steals, monitors, or alters the information in it before sending it on to the machine that it was intended for, if it does so at all.\">Man-In-The-Middle Attacks</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20567e1_d20568e1_d20569e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">Command execution (buffer overflow attacks)</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20570e1_d20571e1_d20572e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">Session replay</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"key1665702908800.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/key1665702908800.html\" title=\"When you deploy and configure the web application you need to ensure that the application is securely deployed. To do so, the passwords and security mechanisms provided with Uniface must be changed and secured.\">Web Application Configuration and Deployment</a>\n</p>\n</td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__2\">\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20573e1_d20574e1_d20575e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"ajn1665702669971.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/ajn1665702669971.html\" title=\"Eavesdropping is a web security threat in which intermediate servers or sniffer programs intercept and read HTTP data packets as they traverse intermediate servers en route to their destination.\">Eavesdropping</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20576e1_d20577e1_d20578e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"kcf1665702669602.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/kcf1665702669602.html\" title=\"When trying to crack user passwords, attackers can resort to guessing, dictionary attacks, and brute force attacks.\">Password Cracking</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"xwm1665702708046.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/xwm1665702708046.html\" title=\"Auditing access and activity logs on a regular basis helps in detecting attempted or successful intrusions. If there has been unauthorized access of your web application, you need to be able to show the signs of intrusion and prove a user's actions. You should also minimize the information provided in error pages.\">Logging and Auditing Web Applications</a>\n</p>\n</td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"fct1665702908434__table_d3998e1_d3999e1_d4000e1__entry__2\">\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20579e1_d20580e1_d20581e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"pxc1665702669673.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/pxc1665702669673.html\" title=\"Data leaks can result from incorrectly specified cookies, unverified client input, and verbose error messages.\">Data Leaks</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20582e1_d20583e1_d20584e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"jkx1665702743178.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/jkx1665702743178.html\" title=\"A denial of service attack attempts to make a computer resource unavailable to its intended users.\">Denial of Service Attack</a>\n</p>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"fct1665702908434__li_d20585e1_d20586e1_d20587e1\">\n<p class=\"p\">Buffer overflow attacks to gain access to system-level details</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2527449\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2527449\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Web Application Vulnerablities Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Okt 06, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Web Application Vulnerablities Almost every area of a web application, from configuration to data I/O, and from auuthentication to logging needs to be considered when looking at web security. In general you need to be consider the following issues when developing your web application: Identity spoofing—you need to prevent users from acting as if they were any other user, or assuming another user's identity. For more details, see Authentication for Web Applications and Session Management for Web Applications . Data tampering—users can change any data delivered to them and this can change client-side validation, GET data, POST data, cookies, HTTP headers, and so on. The application should not send data to the browser that is obtainable from within the browser itself. In addition, the application should carefully check any data received from the user to identify if it is sane and applicable. For more information, see Data I/O for Web Applications . Elevation of privilege—if an application provides users and administrative roles, it is vital to ensure the users cannot elevate themselves to any higher privilege role, by ensuring all actions must be gated through an authorization matrix to ensure that only the right roles can access privileged functionality. For more information, see Authorization for Web Applications . Information disclosure—the browser cannot be trusted fully to adhere to no-caching policies that can be set by HTTP headers. It is therefore important to minimize the amount of information stored by a browser, just in case it leaks information that could be used by an attacker to learn more about the user or even become that user. For more information, see Browser Security . Denial of service—applications could be abused by a denial-of-service attack, in which requests claim expensive resources, thereby impairing service to other users. Such requests should be reserved for authorized users. See Authentication for Web Applications and Authorization for Web Applications . Repudiation—applications should have repudiation controls, such as web access logs and audit trails at every tier as well as a user context from top to bottom. Ideally the application should run as the user, but within Uniface this is not possible. See Logging and Auditing Web Applications . The following table shows the application areas that need to be considered in a web application, and the types of threats they are vulnerable to. The discussions of the security threats include information on how you can defend against them. Table 1. Vulnerable Application Areas and Their Threats Vulnerable Application Area Threats Authentication for Web Applications Session Fixation Session Sidejacking Cross-Site Scripting Man-In-The-Middle Attacks Identity Spoofing Password Cracking Authorization for Web Applications Access to confidential data Data manipulation Execution of unauthorized commands Privilege escalation Browser Security Eavesdropping Data Leaks Cross-Site Scripting Session Management for Web Applications Session Fixation Session Sidejacking Cross-Site Scripting Data I/O for Web Applications Interpreter Injection Cross-Site Scripting Man-In-The-Middle Attacks Command execution (buffer overflow attacks) Session replay Web Application Configuration and Deployment Eavesdropping Password Cracking Logging and Auditing Web Applications Data Leaks Denial of Service Attack Buffer overflow attacks to gain access to system-level details Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}